article.description: Kaitlin Sowinski had 20 points, 15 rebounds and five blocks to help Sacred Heart beat Saint Francis, Pa., 74-66 and win the Northeast Conference tournament championship Sunday.
article.headline: Sacred Heart earns NCAA bid with win over Saint Francis
article.linkText: Sacred Heart earns NEC title in 21st straight win
article.story:
FAIRFIELD, Conn. -- Sacred Heart players gave the freshly cut down net from their second-ever Northeast Conference tournament title to Lisa Moray's parents.

The former Sacred Heart player was tragically killed in June in a car accident after graduating last year. The team dedicated its season to her.

"These kids have been through a tough year," Pioneers coach Ed Swanson said. "They lost one of their best friends. We would trade everything to have Lisa back."

Kaitlin Sowinski had 20 points, 15 rebounds and five blocks to help Sacred Heart beat Saint Francis, Pa., 74-66 and win the tournament championship Sunday.

"It makes it that much more memorable and meaningful for every single person on our team that we were able to accomplish that," senior Stephanie Ryan said.

Sacred Heart (25-7) has won 21 straight games and is tied with Wisconsin-Green Bay for the second-longest winning streak in the nation behind Connecticut. The Pioneers, who last lost Dec. 28 at Villanova, were also in the NCAAs in 2006.

Samantha Leach and Brittany Lilley scored 15 each to lead Saint Francis (15-17), which won nine NEC titles from 1995-2005. But the Red Flash hadn't even qualified for the conference tournament by finishing in the top eight since that last championship.

They returned this year to extend a long NEC tournament winning streak, with 29 straight victories before Sunday.

"We're aware of it, but we don't talk about it," Saint Francis coach Susan Robinson Fruchtl said. "It's been such a storied program over the years and we need to take pride in that. We're connected to the former players. Once a Red Flash always a Red Flash."

Sowinski averaged a remarkable 26 points in the tournament to earn MVP honors. She had 11 points and eight rebounds in the first half.

"She became the best player in the league in the tournament," Swanson said. "She's had a great career. She's put a lot of work into her game."

Leading 49-45 midway through the second half, Sacred Heart went on a 14-4 run to take command of the game. Sowinski scored the last five points with two layups and a free throw to make it 63-49 with 6:53 left.

The Red Flash weren't done, cutting the deficit to 65-60 on Lilley's layup with 2:20 left, but could get no closer as Sacred Heart went 9-for-10 from the free-throw line over the last 2 minutes.

"I didn't relax until the buzzer went off," said Alisa Apo, who led Sacred Heart with 21 points. "They put so much pressure on us. We were up 12 in the first half and they cut it to four."

Callan Taylor added nine points and 10 rebounds for Sacred Heart, which became the third team in conference history to complete a perfect run through the league. The Pioneers advanced to the final by beating Mount St. Mary's and Monmouth.

"I don't think it's hit me yet," Swanson said. "No other team can beat that record. I don't think they felt the impact of what they truly accomplished."

It's been a remarkable turnaround for the Red Flash, who were 6-23 last season. Saint Francis won 12 of its final 16 games, with three of it losses coming against Sacred Heart.

The Pioneers jumped out to a 13-4 lead as Saint Francis missed its first seven shots from the field. Apo had six points during the opening burst. Britney Hodges finally ended the nearly 7-minute drought for the Red Flash with a pullup jumper from the free-throw line.

Sacred Heart extended the advantage to 13 before the Red Flash closed the half on a 15-6 run, capped by Leach's 3-pointer with 43 seconds left to trail 33-29 at the break. Saint Francis had missed its first nine 3-point attempts. The Red Flash finished the game 2-for-18 from behind the arc.

"We started the game off a little tentative," Robinson Fruchtl said. "Some steals got us back in the game before the end of the first half. We shot 32 percent -- you're not going to win many games shooting 32 percent. We missed a lot of open shots."
